1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,724
Patch the Web is a safe repair layer for websites you don't own.

2
00:00:03,724 --> 00:00:12,743
Let me show you the complete flow: downloading the real extension, finding a community fix, and turning a frustrating site into something genuinely useful.

3
00:00:12,749 --> 00:00:17,872
I'm downloading the extension from our public site and opening Chrome's extension page.

4
00:00:17,872 --> 00:00:23,113
For this demo it's loaded unpacked, exactly like a judge can install it from the release.

5
00:00:23,113 --> 00:00:26,410
Using community repairs needs no account and no API key.

6
00:00:26,409 --> 00:00:28,473
Here is MetroCare before the repair.

7
00:00:28,473 --> 00:00:34,609
It lists twelve services, but there is no search, no accessibility filter, and no way to compare providers.

8
00:00:34,609 --> 00:00:39,025
Finding wheelchair-accessible care in your language means reading every card.

9
00:00:39,026 --> 00:00:43,835
When I open Patch the Web, it finds a community repair written for this exact page.

10
00:00:43,835 --> 00:00:52,469
Before showing Install, the extension checks the publisher policy, the patch's cryptographic hash, and all eleven selectors against the live website.

11
00:00:52,470 --> 00:00:53,569
Now I install it.

12
00:00:53,569 --> 00:00:58,097
The repair is a constrained data document, never arbitrary JavaScript.

13
00:00:58,097 --> 00:01:05,405
Every operation is allow-listed, every selector was preflighted, and the permission applies only to this website.

14
00:01:05,406 --> 00:01:08,291
The page now has the feature its owner never built.

15
00:01:08,291 --> 00:01:16,154
I can select two real listings and open a keyboard-accessible comparison, while the original site stays intact underneath the repair layer.

16
00:01:16,157 --> 00:01:21,042
Now I'll filter for wheelchair access, Urdu, and providers accepting new patients.

17
00:01:21,042 --> 00:01:23,306
Twelve cards become one useful result.

18
00:01:23,306 --> 00:01:28,906
Those preferences stay inside this browser; neither MetroCare nor Patch the Web receives them.

19
00:01:28,907 --> 00:01:30,402
I'll reload the website.

20
00:01:30,402 --> 00:01:35,698
The repair runs again automatically, and my unfinished filter choices are still here.

21
00:01:35,698 --> 00:01:40,806
This is a durable browser feature, not a screenshot and not a one-time AI preview.

22
00:01:40,810 --> 00:01:46,703
The extension shows exactly what's active, where it can run, and whether every operation is still healthy.

23
00:01:46,703 --> 00:01:51,485
Permissions remain reviewable, and the user can disable the repair whenever they want.

24
00:01:51,491 --> 00:02:01,621
Codex and GPT-5.6 accelerated the hard part: inspecting DOM and screenshot evidence, authoring the constrained patch, threat-modeling it, and running browser tests.

25
00:02:01,621 --> 00:02:04,709
Everyone else simply installs the verified result.

26
00:02:04,709 --> 00:02:07,921
That's Patch the Web: users fixing the web together.
